# reorG Safety Rules

These rules are non-negotiable across every file, feature, and refactor.

## No Deletion

- NEVER create, reference, or implement marketplace listing deletion logic
- NEVER create API endpoints, service functions, UI buttons, or code paths that delete listings
- If an SDK/API client exposes delete methods, do not call them — do not even import them
- If a pull request introduces any delete-adjacent code for listings, reject it

## No Silent Writes

- NEVER push data to any marketplace without explicit user confirmation
- Every push must go through: write lock check → dry-run → user confirmation → execute → audit log
- Sync is always pull-only — it must never write to any marketplace
- Sync must never overwrite StagedChange records; it only updates MarketplaceListing (live values)

## Staged Value Protection

- StagedChange is a separate table from MarketplaceListing
- When sync runs, it updates MarketplaceListing fields — never StagedChange
- Autosaved edits create/update StagedChange records — they never directly mutate MarketplaceListing
- A staged value persists until the user explicitly pushes or cancels it

## Environment Guards

- Staging environment (`stage.reorg.theperfectpart.net`) is write-protected by default
- Check `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV` and enforce write blocks in staging unless explicitly overridden
- Production must launch with write locks easily accessible and controllable

## Backup Safety

- v1 backups are export/download only
- Do not implement automated restore-to-marketplace functionality in v1
- Architecture may be future-ready for restore, but no restore execution code in v1

## Secrets

- Never log, return in API responses, or render in client components: API keys, tokens, passwords, connection strings
- Use server-only environment variables; prefix public-safe values with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`
- Never commit `.env` files to git
